In the first version of the code you posted, you just kept the maximum value in an integer. That was fine if you wanted to find the value, but the information which node it was was lost.

In comments, I proposed you make `max` a node. You did that, but made several errors:

  * You `max` is uninitialized, which means that bad things will happen. (C-speak for that is &quot;undefined behaviour&quot;.) Initialize `max = start`. (Seeing a pointer definition without initialization should raise a red flag. If you don&#39;t know what to initialize, at least make it `NULL`, so that you can do checks for `NULL` later. Just writing `struct node *max;` means that `max` has an indeterminate value which you can&#39;t even check!
  * Then, when you find a better node, don&#39;t set `max-&gt;total`. That means that you just use the first node as storage for your max, thereby altering the list data, which you don&#39;t want. Set the new node:

        if (new1-&gt;total &gt; max-&gt;total) max = new1;

    (If you read my comment closely, that&#39;s what I proposed.)

Let&#39;s implement that and also fix some semantic issues with the code, see notes below:

    const struct *node maximumNode()
    {
        const struct node *node = start;
        const struct node *max = start;
    
        while (node != NULL) {
            if(node-&gt;total &gt; max-&gt;total) {
                max = node;
            }
    
            node = node-&gt;right;
        }
        
        return max;
    }

Things to note:

  * The function now returns a reference to the node with maximum `total`. The calling code can then print the info or use the node in other ways as it desires, for example:

        const struct node *max = maximumNode();

        if (node) {
            printf(&quot;Max. total of %d was on day %d.\n&quot;,
                node-&gt;totel, node-&gt;day;
        }

    This is cleaner than doing the printing in the function proper. This wil also allow you to use the same function in other contexts where you need the max. node.
  * I&#39;ve made the node pointers `const struct node *` in your functions. That means that you cannot modify the content of the structs. Just finding the max means that you merely inspect the list, but don&#39;&#196;t alter it. With this declaration, the compiler would have complained about trying to set `max-&gt;total` and you would have seen your error.
  * You don&#39;t need the first test for `NULL`. When `start`== NULL`, then also `node == NULL` and `max == NULL`. That doesn&#39;t change, because the loop isn&#39;t entered and we terurn `NULL`, which is the best we can do in that case.
  * I&#39;ve changed the name of the node from `new1` to just `node`. That&#39;s a cosmetic change, but `new` to me suggests that a node is being created, but as we&#39;re only inspecting, that name may be misleading. Little things count. (Also, I&#39;m a nitpicker.)

