The suite is currently set up like the following:

```
describe(&quot;top level&quot;, () =&gt; {
    beforeEach(() =&gt; {
        doInitialSetup(initialParameters = defaultParams); 
    });
    
    afterEach(() =&gt; {
        doTeardown(); 
    });
    
    it(&quot;Should do the thing when initial parameters are default&quot;, () =&gt; {
        // Standard test code
    });
    
    /*
    
    [Lots more tests like the above]
    
    */
    
    it(&quot;Should behave like A when the initial parameters are X&quot;, () =&gt; {
        // ??? 
    });

    it(&quot;Should behave like B when the initial parameters are Y&quot;, () =&gt; {
        // ??? 
    });

    describe(&quot;Everything in this nested suite should have the initialParameters as default&quot;, () =&gt; {
        // Nested suite
    });

    describe(&quot;Everything in this nested suite should have the initialParameters set to X&quot;, () =&gt; {
        // ???
    });
});
```

A number of less than ideal solutions that I can see:

- Have a unique top level suite for every possible configuration of initial parameters. This is not ideal because it breaks the nice property of related areas being tested being grouped in the test suite tree.
- Abandon beforeEach() entirely and manually call the setup function in every test case. This is not ideal because it adds boilerplate to every single test case, including the majority of cases which are happy to have the initial setup set up as default.

Anyone have any better ideas?

