Two important things first of all.

In your theme code in the header.php file
check for **wp_head()** function; in the file.
The **wp_head()** function is responsible for displaying titles, scripts, styles, goals and other information that comes from plugins, actions, and wordpress panel settings automatically. Then it must be present in all wordpress headers or you will have various errors and difficulties during development.

        &lt;html &lt;?php language_attributes(); ?&gt;&gt;
            &lt;head&gt;
                &lt;!-- ... other codes ...--&gt;

                &lt;!-- This wp_head function must be present in all wordpress headers. --&gt;
                &lt;?php wp_head(); ?&gt;
            &lt;/head&gt;

Another important thing is the function: **wp_footer()**
It is responsible for calling extra information like scripts and other settings similar to **wp_head();** and she must always be present in the example&#39;s footer.php:

 		&lt;!-- ... other codes ...--&gt;
		&lt;?php wp_footer(); ?&gt;

	&lt;/body&gt;
	&lt;/html&gt;

Now to create blocks with gutenberg you can add custom code to your needs in the functions.php file, but when changing themes it will not appear in the panel.
I suggest you create a plugin that will contain the new codes.

For more information you should consult:
https://developer.wordpress.org/block-editor/developers/
and
https://developer.wordpress.org/plugins/

For rendering blocks note that you must call inside the file the following sample code:

	if ( have_posts() ) {
		while ( have_posts() ) {
			the_post(); 
			//
			the_content(); //responsible for rendering
			//
		} // end while
	} // end if

You can create one more `LiveData` for the language, and use [switchMap][1] to map it to the translations, like:
```kotlin
class translationViewmodel(private val database: TranslationDatabaseDao, initLanguage: String): ViewModel() {
  val language = MutableLiveData&lt;String&gt;(&quot;en&quot;)
  val translations = language.switchMap { language -&gt; 
    database.getTranslations(language)
  }
  ...
}
```
Now, just change the language and translations will be updated too
```kotlin
viewmodel.language.value = &quot;es&quot;
```

  [1]: https://developer.android.com/reference/android/arch/lifecycle/Transformations.html#switchmap

